column10:
This is a specialisation of hc::protocol. Description focused on the concept of effort as distinct from the survey method itself. The method of applying effort relates to the intensity of sampling of an area and therefore can assist in interpreting measures of completeness of survey coverage. 
A description of the number and arrangement of sensors deployed; whether sensors were mobile or stationary; how frequently observations, measurements or samples were taken; etc. Sensors may be mobile or stationary detection entities such as people, camera traps and other types of physical traps, nets, sonic spectrum detectors, drones and other aerial platforms, proximity detectors, etc.

column9: A description of or reference to (publication, URI) the method or rationale originally used to assess reported taxonomic completeness.
column10:
This term allows data users to determine how comprehensively an area has been surveyed, which assists in interpreting species populations, area of occupancy, etc. 
Include the method undertaken to assess reported completeness or an explanation about the basis of the reported completeness. Information about taxonomic completeness is useful to understand if an area has been adequately surveyed and allows inference about species absences. If many descriptions applicable, separate them with space vertical bar space ( | ).
